726621f-c.text:
Flushing Meadow Park (ueens): A former golf club house, on the east side of 111th Street and 46th Avenue, which was razed for the development of this area into part of the World's Fair grounds. The Railroads Building of the Fair was later erected here.
November 2, 1936
Views 1,2,3
P. L. Sperr

726623f-a.text:
Flushing Meadow Park (Oueens): Vfewing north across the western extremity of the park and showing a small community in Corona, along 111th Street, before this area was incorporated into the New York World's Fair grounds of 1939-4O. All the homes were Nraaed and the area filled in and leveled out; the Corona gates and the Aveation, Chrysler Motors and Railroads Buildirms were erected here. On the left is the roof of Public School No. 17, on the west side of 111th Street and 51st Avenue. That side of
the street remained intact.
View 2 shows the same area in the opposite direction, i.e., looking south from 47th Avenue; 111th Street and P. S. 17 are on
the right.
View 3 is i-: the same direction as view 1, from 51st Avenue.
View 1: October 2, 1935
View 2: November 2, 1936
View 3: Wovember 10, 1936
P. L. Sperr
